Estimate the weight added to each section of the vehicle while towing. This includes any added weight placed inside the vehicle cabin, such as passengers, luggage, etc.

Note: For two-door vehicles, consider only the 1st row and the rear cabin storage as the 3rd row

Adding accessories to the vehicle increases its overall weight. Pre-determined values are provided for each accessory for convenience, but actual weights may vary depending on factors such as material and brand. If you have the exact weight of your accessories, you can adjust each one accordingly.

Alternatively, if you have additional accessories not listed, you can include them under others

Simply select the total weight of what you are towing, regardless of the type of trailer (whether it's a boat, caravan, camper trailer, float, trailer, or other).
Select the total weight of the trailer before it's hitched to your vehicle, also known as the ATM (Aggregate Trailer Mass).

A default assumption of 10% of the overall trailer weight is used to determine the towball download weight. However, if you know the exact towball download weight and wish to override this default, you can input the precise value.

Axle Analysis & Load Distribution: Use this tool to enter your vehicle configurations, adjust your payload loading, and more to see how weight is distributed across your axles. Please note, this is only an estimate and actual conditions may vary. For accurate results and safety, always consult a professional or your vehicle manufacturer.

The max rear axle load refers to the maximum weight that can be safely supported by the vehicle's rear axle, as specified by the manufacturer. It's essential for ensuring proper load balance, stability, and safety, particularly when towing or carrying heavy loads.

Our paid version accesses manufacturer specifications and, where possible, retrieves the max rear axle load for your vehicle automatically. This ensures you have accurate data to support safe load distribution and optimal towing performance.

The wheelbase length is the distance between the centers of the front and rear axles, measured in millimeters (mm). This measurement affects the vehicles stability, handling, and overall ride comfort, especially when towing or carrying heavy loads. A longer wheelbase typically improves stability, while a shorter wheelbase may offer better maneuverability.

Our paid version accesses manufacturer specifications and, where possible, retrieves the wheelbase length for your vehicle automatically. This ensures you have accurate data for optimizing your towing setup and load distribution.

The rear overhang length is the distance from the rear axle to the very end of the vehicles rear, measured in millimeters (mm). This measurement affects the leverage on the rear axle, which can influence vehicle stability, especially when towing or carrying heavy loads. A longer rear overhang may increase the vehicle's susceptibility to sway.

Our paid version accesses manufacturer specifications and, where possible, retrieves the rear overhang length for your vehicle automatically. This helps ensure accurate data for balancing your load and improving towing performance.

Max Axle Load Rating: This value indicates the maximum load that the front and rear axles of your vehicle can safely support, as specified by the manufacturer. When available, this information is auto-populated based on vehicle details. If this field is empty, please refer to your vehicle's manual to find the maximum axle load rating.

Payload Weight Rating: This rating represents the distribution of your vehicle's weight across the front and rear axles based on its geometry. By default, the weight distribution is set at 55% for the front axle and 45% for the rear axle, which applies to most vehicles. If your vehicle requires a different distribution due to specific design or usage needs, you can customize these percentages accordingly in this field.

Towball Leverage Rating: This rating quantifies the increased force exerted on the rear axle when weight is applied to the towball. It is calculated based on the vehicle's wheelbase and rear overhang measurements. If we have these details available, this value will be auto-populated. Otherwise, a default value of 150% is used, which serves as a general rule of thumb for most vehicles. You can customize this value to better fit the specific towing dynamics of your vehicle.

Axle Analysis: This feature provides the final estimation of your axle ratings, factoring in your input and various setup configurations. It consolidates the impact of accessories, payload, towing configuration, and Weight Distribution Hitch (WDH) use into a comprehensive analysis. Note that this is an estimate only; always consult a professional for precise evaluations and use this information strictly as a guideline to ensure safety and compliance in your towing setup.

Towball Download: This figure represents the weight of your caravan as it is applied to the towball of your towing vehicle. A default value of 10% of the caravan's weight is typically used as a general rule of thumb. If you have precise information about your setup, you can customize this value to reflect the actual towball weight to ensure accurate load distribution and towing stability.
